{"title_page": "Shammai Engelmayer", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{POV|date=September 2018}}{{citation style|date=September 2018|details=It is unclear what the purposes of many citations in the article are. For example, the claim that Engelmayer was married to Roslyn Engelmayer is supported by a link to a report on Supreme Court cases.}}{{disputed|date=September 2018}}}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Shammai Engelmayer\n|image       = File:Rabbi Shammai Engelmayer.jpg\n|alt         = photograph\n|birth_name  = Sheldon David Engelmayer\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1945|7|26}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n| education  =\n|occupation  = Pulpit rabbi, Jewish commentator\n|known_for   = Jewish law columnist, social advocacy, political commentary\n|spouse      =  Roslyn Engelmayer <br />[[Marilyn Henry]] (deceased)\n|children    = 3\n|website     = [http://shammai.org/ Shammai Engelmayer]\n}}\n'''Sheldon David Engelmayer''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e9\u05de\u05d0\u05d9}}; born July 26, 1945) is a full-time pulpit rabbi at the Temple Israel Community Center, an egalitarian Conservative synagogue in [[Cliffside Park, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Beck_RabbiShammai\">{{cite news |last1=Beck |first1=Leslie Ann |title=This is a Giving Community |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/pittsfield-berkshire-eagle-nov-09-2006-p-27/ |work=[[The Berkshire Eagle|Pittsfield Berkshire Eagle]] |publisher=New England Newspapers Inc. |date=9 November 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Santora_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Santora |first1=Rev. Alexander |title=Faith Matters: Congregations merge to form new community for the future |url=https://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2015/10/faith_matters_congregations_merge_to_form_new_comm.html |work=NJ.com |publisher=Advance Local Media LLC |date=27 October 2015}}</ref>  He is the author of eight nonfiction books on topics ranging from corporate irresponsibility in the [[A.H. Robins]] Company's [[Dalkon Shield]] intrauterine device case, to biographies of public figures, including [[Hubert Humphrey]] and [[Martha Mitchell]].\n\n==History==\n===Media and journalism===\nIn 1967, Engelmayer was a features editor for ''[[The Jewish Press]]'', an American weekly newspaper based in Brooklyn, New York.<!-- This citation appears to have nothing to do with his role as a features editor<ref name=\"CongRec113-30\">{{cite journal |last1=Tenzer |first1=Herbert |editor1-last=Engelmayer |editor1-first=Sheldon |title=Job Discrimination Desk |journal=113 Cong. Rec. (Bound) - Volume 113, Part 31 (February 1, 1967 to December 15, 1967) |date=21 February 1967 |volume=113 |issue=31 |url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/GPO-CRECB-1967-pt31/pdf/GPO-CRECB-1967-pt31.pdf |series=Congressional Record |publisher=United States House of Representatives |language=En}}</ref>--><ref name=\"Jewish Press\">{{cite news |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Shammai |title=Jerusalem, Frisch, and Jewish law |url=http://blogs.timesofisrael.com/jerusalem-frisch-and-jewish-law/ |work=The Jewish Standard |publisher=Times of Israel |date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\nHe then became an associate editor with the [[North American Newspaper Alliance]] (NANA);<ref name=\"Sid_Goldberg\">{{cite news |last1=Associated |first1=Press |title=News Service to End 58 Years of Operation |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/nashua-telegraph-feb-21-1980-p-20/ |work=The Nashua Telegraph |agency=The Nutting Company |publisher=Ogden Newspapers |date=21 February 1980 |archivedate=2 September 2015 |location=New Hampshire |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/> at the age of 25, Engelmayer became the editor.<ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/><ref name=\"Mosquitia\">{{cite book |last1=Rangel |first1=Marc |title=Memories of Mosquitia |date=2009 |publisher=Xlibris Corporation |isbn=9781477163191 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LJ5W6Ey6nq0C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"SDE_Liddy\">{{cite news |last1=Wire Story |title=Ford Linked to Job Assist for Liddy |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/phoenix-arizona-republic-oct-16-1973-p-21/ |work=The Arizona Republic |agency=Associated Press |publisher=USA Today Network |date=16 October 1973 |language=en}}</ref>  [[United Features Syndicate]] (UFS) acquired and absorbed NANA, and from 1972 to 1979, Engelmayer edited under the banner of UFS.<ref name=\"UFS_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon |last2=Ashman |first2=Charles |title=Nixon Leaves pepsi firm, Meets Mitchell, Martha Meets the Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/101240600/ |work=The Cincinnati Enquirer |publisher=USA Today Network |date=25 July 1973 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe became the first editor of [[Jack Anderson (columnist)|Jack Anderson]]'s \"[[Washington Merry-Go-Round]]\" column and was a part of Anderson's winning of the [[Pulitzer Prize]].<ref name=\"BW_SDE\">{{cite news |title=Future Events |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=27kiAQAAMAAJ&dq= |work=[[Business Week]] |issue=2287-2294 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |date=1973}}</ref><ref name=\"palmer_Mask\">{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Joanne |title=The man in the mask |url=http://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/the-man-in-the-mask/ |work=Jewish Standard |publisher=Times of Israel |date=26 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis own investigative work writing about the American natural gas shortage in the Seventies won him the [[Thomas L. Stokes]] Award for National Reporting, Washington Journalism Center.<ref name=\"Stokes Award_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Robert |last2=Engelmayer |first2=Sheldon |title=Public Utilities Skirt Gas Issue |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/high-point-enterprise-may-03-1976-p-1/ |work=High Point Enterprise |agency=hpenews.com |date=3 May 1976 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Star News\">{{cite news |last1=Associated |first1=Press |title=S-N Columnists Win Stokes Writing Prize |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/star-news-mar-16-1976-p-15/ |work=Star News |agency=Associated Press |date=16 March 1976 |archiveurl= |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s and 1980s, Engelmayer was almost a regular on the [[Barry Farber]] radio show, with Farber calling him \"the big Shamm\",<ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=SSSJ Events, 1964-1991. Boxes 1-51 and Oversized Boxes 197 & 385 |url=http://libfindaids.yu.edu:8082/xtf/view?docId=ead/SSSJ/SSSJ.xml;query=;brand=default |website=Yeshiva University Archives |publisher=Yeshiva University |location=Mendel Gottesman Library |page=248}}</ref> referring to his Hebrew name, Shammai, which he began using professionally once he became a pulpit rabbi.<ref name=\"CBI_Palisades\">{{cite web |title=Meet Our Rabbi |url=http://cbiotp.org/Our-Rabbi.html |website=cbiotp.org |publisher=CONGREGATION BETH ISRAELOF THE PALISADES}}</ref><ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/>\n\nIn the early 1980s, Engelmayer replaced David Gross as the executive editor of the ''[[New York Jewish Week]]'',<ref name=\"JTA_SDEJW\">{{cite news |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon |title=Full-Term Miracle, May 14, 1948 |url=http://ufdc.ufl.edu/AA00010090/03145 |work=The Jewish Floridian |agency=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |issue=19 |volume=62|date=12 May 1989 |page=5}}</ref><ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/><ref name=\"JJG_SDE\">{{cite book |last1=Goldberg |first1=J.J. |title=Jewish power : inside the American Jewish establishment |date=1996 |publisher=[[Basic Books]] |location=Reading, Mass. |isbn=9780201622423 |page=xi |edition= 3rd printing |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Jewish_Power.html?id=BwV2AAAAMAAJ}}</ref><ref name=\"Gross_Dies\">{{cite news |title=News Brief {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency |url=https://www.jta.org/2005/09/28/archive/david-gross-a-former-writer-for-jta-and |work=www.jta.org |publisher=JTA |date=28 September 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"Bard-Gross\">{{cite book |last1=Bard |first1=Mitchell G. |title=From tragedy to triumph : the politics behind the rescue of Ethiopian Jewry |date=2002 |publisher=[[Praeger Publishing]] |location=Westport (Conn.) |isbn=9780275970000 |page=153 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sjO8JOSKDCMC&dq=David+Gross+Jewish+Week&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> a New York-based Jewish issues weekly newspaper.  He left in 1991 and took a post as director of communications for the [[Jewish Theological Seminary of America|Jewish Theological Seminary]] in New York City,<ref name=\"JTS_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Wire |title=Bat Mitzvah Pioneer Marks Another Religious Milsteon |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sedalia-democrat-mar-20-1992-p-3/ |work=Sedalia Democrat |agency=Associated Press |date=20 March 1992}}</ref><ref name=\"DNC_Shammai\">{{cite news |last1=Nussbaum Cohen |first1=Debra |title=Camp\u2019s Decision to Censor Magazine Illustrates Rift Among Conservatives {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency |url=https://www.jta.org/1994/09/30/archive/camps-decision-to-censor-magazine-illustrates-rift-among-conservatives |work=Daily News Bulletin |agency=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |publisher=www.jta.org |date=30 September 1994}}</ref> where he also renewed his rabbinical ordination, preparing him for his pulpit position.\n\nHe was also briefly the editor of the ''[[MetroWest Jewish News]]'' from 1996-1998.<ref name=\"Lorell_SDEMW\">{{cite news |last1=Lorell |first1=Mark |title=Congressional report warns:  War in Middle East is imminent {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency |url=https://www.jta.org/1997/06/05/life-religion/features/congressional-report-warns-war-in-middle-east-is-imminent |work=www.jta.org |agency=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |date=5 June 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, Engelmayer established an award-winning column (\"Keeping the Faith\") for the New Jersey-based weekly newspaper ''[[The Jewish Standard]]'', in which he discusses current issues through the prism of Jewish law. He was the editor of ''The Jewish Standard'' until he resigned in 2012. He continued his weekly column, but now had time to teach and run his synagogue, which has since merged with three other synagogues that were dwindling in numbers and looking for new leadership.<ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/><ref name=\"Shabbus\">{{cite news |last1=Santora |first1=Alexander |title=Jews in North Bergen get a Shab-Bus to shul |url=https://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2014/11/jews_in_north_bergen_get_a_shab-bus_to_shul.html |work=[[Jersey Journal]] |agency=NJ.com |date=19 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"CommMarriage\">{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Joanne |title=A community marriage |url=https://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/a-community-marriage/ |work=[[The Jewish Standard]] |publisher=Times of Israel |date=5 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"SSB_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Solomon Bernstein |first1=Susan |title=Temple Beth El Has Closed, But It is Not Gone |url=https://zicharonot.com/2016/01/15/temple-beth-el-has-closed-but-it-is-not-gone/ |work=zicharonot |date=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, he and his frequent writing partner, Robert Wagman, NANA's Washington, D.C., bureau chief, produced a documentary called ''The Making of [[Lion of the Desert]]'',<ref name=\"MakinLOTD\">{{cite web |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon |last2=Wagman |first2=Bob |title=The Making of Lion of the Desert |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2983612/ |date=1981}}</ref> a film about pre-WWII fascist Italy, starring [[Anthony Quinn]], [[Oliver Reed]], and [[Rod Steiger]].\n\n===Rabbinate===\nOrdained as an [[Orthodox Jewish]] rabbi in 1967,<ref name=\"TBEBC\">{{cite web |title=Rabbi Shammai Englemayer |url=http://www.templebethelofnorthbergen.org/about/rabbi-shammai-englemeyer/ |website=Temple Beth El of North Bergen |publisher=Temple Beth El Bergen County}}</ref> he chose the field of journalism.  In 1992, while working at the Jewish Theological Society he also enrolled in rabbinate courses and recertified his ordination through the Conservative Jewish movement. His first pulpit was the Lake [[Hopatcong, New Jersey|Hopatcong]] Jewish Center in New Jersey.<ref name=\"Common_Ground\">{{cite book |last1=Ozarowski |first1=Joseph S. |last2=Engelmayer |first2=Shammai |last3=Sofian |first3=David M. |editor1-last=Lipman |editor1-first=Steve |title=Common ground : the weekly Torah portion through the eyes of a Conservative, Orthodox, and Reform rabbi |date=1997 |publisher=[[Jason Aronson]] |location=Northvale, N.J. |isbn=9780765759924 |page=391 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=03T6u7nh9MQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>  He would find a congregation closer to his home, Temple Israel in [[Cliffside Park, New Jersey|Cliffside Park]], and merged with other neighboring congregations.<ref name=\"CommMarriage\"/>\n\n===Personal life===\nEngelmayer was married to Roslyn Engelmayer,<ref name=\"NYSC\">{{cite journal |title=Reports of cases decided in the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of the state of New York |date=1978 |page=756 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0a5OAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=8 August 2011 |publisher=the University of California |location=Digitized |language=en |quote=Alimony}}</ref> and then to the writer, [[Marilyn Henry]], who died in 2011.<ref name=\"Boroson\">{{cite news |last1=Boroson |first1=Rebbecca |title=Former \u2018Post\u2019 staffer Marilyn Henry dies, 58 |url=https://www.jpost.com/Features/In-Thespotlight/Former-Post-staffer-Marilyn-Henry-dies-58 |work=The Jerusalem Post |publisher=JPost.com |date=3 March 2011}}</ref> He has three children and lives in [[Teaneck, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Boroson\"/>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n* [[Simon Rockower Award|Rockower Award]] in 2011 for Commentary/2nd place, The Standard (for an article on President Obama's stance on Israel.<ref name=\"Obama\">{{cite news |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Shammai |title=Obama\u2019s distorted Israel image |url=https://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/obamas-distorted-israel-image-4/ |work=The Standard |publisher=Times of Israel |date=6 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"JTA2013Rock\">{{cite news |last1=JTA Staff |title=Excellence in Jewish journalism: The Rockower Awards {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency |url=https://www.jta.org/2013/06/28/news-opinion/the-telegraph/excellence-in-jewish-journalism-the-rockower-awards |work=www.jta.org |agency=Jewsish Telegraphic Agency |date=28 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AJYB2013\">{{cite book |last1=Sheskin |first1=edited by Arnold Dashefsky, Ira |title=American Jewish Year Book 2013 The Annual Record of the North American Jewish Communities |date=2014 |publisher=Springer International Publishing |location=Cham |isbn=9783319016580 |page=817 |edition= Aufl. 2014 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FQTABAAAQBAJ&dq=}}</ref> It is noteworthy is that back in 1978\u201379 Engelmayer had held President [[Jimmy Carter]] accountable for what he and his co-author Robert Wagman called \"broken promises\" over wage and price controls, defence spending, and nuclear proliferation.<ref name=\"Carter_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Wagman |first1=Robert |last2=Engelmayer |first2=Sheldon |title=Promises, Promises, More Broken Promises, Part II |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/santa-ana-orange-county-register-evening-feb-27-1979-p-4/ |work=[[Santa Ana Orange County Register]] |publisher=Southern California News Group |date=27 February 1979 |page=B17}}</ref>\n* Rockower Award in 2010 - First Place for Editorial Writing,<ref name=\"AJPA2010\">{{cite web |last1=Category 4: Award for Excellence in Editorial Writing |title=The 31st Annual Simon Rockower Award Winners - American Jewish Press Association |url=https://www.ajpa.org/page/2012RockowerAwards |website=www.ajpa.org}}</ref> in 2005 for Commentary/2nd place, [[American Jewish Press Association]], Rockower Award for Commentary/2nd place, AJPA, 2004, Rockower Award for Editorial Writing/1st place, American Jewish Press Association, 1990\n* Rockower Award for Editorial Writing/2nd place, AJPA, 1989\n* Rockower Award for Editorial Writing/1st place, AJPA, 1988,<ref name=\"E&P1988\">{{cite book |title=Editor & Publisher |date=1990 |publisher=Editor & Publisher Company |page=2 |edition= Vol 123 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CU1IAQAAIAAJ&q=Rockower+Award+1988+Engelmayer&dq=Rockower+Award+1988+Engelmayer&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTqMOXjMzcAhUE74MKHYBoBksQ6AEIKTAA |language=en}}</ref>\n* Thomas L. Stokes Award for National Reporting, Washington Journalism Center, 1975<ref name=\"Hostage\">{{cite book |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon D. |last2=Wagman |first2=Robert J. |title=Hostage |date=1981 |publisher=Caroline House Publishers |location=Ottawa, Ill. |isbn=0898030846 |url=https://www.amazon.com/HOSTAGE-OP-Sheldon-D-Engelmayer/dp/0898030846/ref=sr_1_4?ie=UTF8&qid=1533152692&sr=8-4&}}</ref>\n* In 1975, he won the Washington Journalism Center's [[Thomas L. Stokes]] Award for National Reporting.<ref name=\"Star News\"/>\n* Media Humanitarian Award, National Association of Justice, 1974\n\n==Books==\n* ''Martha: The Mouth that Roared''<ref name=\"MM\">{{cite book |last1=Ashman |first1=Charles |last2=Engelmayer |first2=Sheldon |title=Martha: The Mouth That Roared |date=1973 |publisher=Berkley |isbn=978-0425024683}}</ref><ref name=\"Ashman_MM\">{{cite news |last1=Ashman |first1=Charles |title=Martha - The Mouth that Roared|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/journal-news-jul-24-1973-p-16|work=Journal News - Hamilton Ohio |agency=Cox Media Group |date=24 July 1973 |archiveurl= |archivedate= |location=Ohio |page=16 |language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Lord's Justice''<ref name=\"Lord'sJustice\">{{cite book |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon |last2=Wagman |first2=Robert |title=Lord's justice |date=1985 |publisher=Anchor Press/Doubleday |location=Garden City, N.Y. |isbn=978-0385230513 |edition=1st |url=https://archive.org/details/lordsjustice00enge }}</ref>\n* ''HUBERT HUMPHREY The man and His Dream''<ref name=\"HubertHumphrey\">{{cite news |last1=Library News |title=Through These Doors |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/huntingdon-daily-news-dec-04-1978-p-17/ |work=Huntingdon Daily News |agency=The Daily News |publisher=Sample News Group |date=4 December 1978 |language=en}}</ref> \n* ''Hostage''<ref name=\"Hostage\"/>\n* ''Tax revolt 1980: A how-to guide''<ref name=\"Tax Revolt\">{{cite book |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon D. |last2=Wagman |first2=Robert J. |title=Tax revolt 1980 : a how-to guide |date=1980 |publisher=Arlington House Publishers |location=Westport, CT |isbn=0870004697 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Tax-revolt-1980-how-guide/dp/0870004697/ref=sr_1_5?ie=UTF8&qid=1533152692&sr=8-5&keywords=}}</ref>\n* ''Where there's smoke (A Last Resort Mystery Book 1)''<ref name=\"Smoke\">{{cite book |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Shammai |title=Where there's smoke |date=27 November 2012 |publisher=Amazon Digital Services LLC |url=https://www.amazon.com/Where-theres-smoke-Resort-Mystery-ebook/dp/B00AEGD1VA/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1533153286&sr=8-1}}</ref>\n* ''Common Ground''<ref name=\"Common_Ground\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/writers/shammai-engelmayer/ Jewish Standard]\n* [http://shammai.org Shammai.org]\n* [http://www.betshammai.com/ Bet Shammai Blog], named for the school of thought of Judaism founded by [[Bet Shammai|Shammai]], a Jewish scholar of the 1st century, whose arguments were the better ones, but were the least adhered to over his rival, [[Bet Hillel]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Engelmayer, Sheldon}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:American Conservative rabbis]]\n[[Category:American Orthodox rabbis]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Teaneck, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rabbis from New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{POV|date=September 2018}}{{citation style|date=September 2018|details=It is unclear what the purposes of many citations in the article are. For example, the claim that Engelmayer was married to Roslyn Engelmayer is supported by a link to a report on Supreme Court cases.}}{{disputed|date=September 2018}}}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Shammai Engelmayer\n|image       = File:Rabbi Shammai Engelmayer.jpg\n|alt         = photograph\n|birth_name  = Sheldon David Engelmayer\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1945|7|26}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n| education  =\n|occupation  = Pulpit rabbi, Jewish commentator\n|known_for   = Jewish law columnist, social advocacy, political commentary\n|spouse      =  Roslyn Engelmayer <br />[[Marilyn Henry]] (deceased)\n|children    = 3\n|website     = [http://shammai.org/ Shammai Engelmayer]\n}}\n'''Sheldon David Engelmayer''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e9\u05de\u05d0\u05d9}}; born July 26, 1945) is a full-time pulpit rabbi at the Temple Israel Community Center, an egalitarian Conservative synagogue in [[Cliffside Park, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Beck_RabbiShammai\">{{cite news |last1=Beck |first1=Leslie Ann |title=This is a Giving Community |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/pittsfield-berkshire-eagle-nov-09-2006-p-27/ |work=[[The Berkshire Eagle|Pittsfield Berkshire Eagle]] |publisher=New England Newspapers Inc. |date=9 November 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Santora_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Santora |first1=Rev. Alexander |title=Faith Matters: Congregations merge to form new community for the future |url=https://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2015/10/faith_matters_congregations_merge_to_form_new_comm.html |work=NJ.com |publisher=Advance Local Media LLC |date=27 October 2015}}</ref>  He is the author of eight nonfiction books on topics ranging from corporate irresponsibility in the [[A.H. Robins]] Company's [[Dalkon Shield]] intrauterine device case, to biographies of public figures, including [[Hubert Humphrey]] and [[Martha Mitchell]].\n\n==History==\n===Media and journalism===\nIn 1967, Engelmayer was a features editor for ''[[The Jewish Press]]'', an American weekly newspaper based in Brooklyn, New York.<!-- This citation appears to have nothing to do with his role as a features editor<ref name=\"CongRec113-30\">{{cite journal |last1=Tenzer |first1=Herbert |editor1-last=Engelmayer |editor1-first=Sheldon |title=Job Discrimination Desk |journal=113 Cong. Rec. (Bound) - Volume 113, Part 31 (February 1, 1967 to December 15, 1967) |date=21 February 1967 |volume=113 |issue=31 |url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/GPO-CRECB-1967-pt31/pdf/GPO-CRECB-1967-pt31.pdf |series=Congressional Record |publisher=United States House of Representatives |language=En}}</ref>--><ref name=\"Jewish Press\">{{cite news |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Shammai |title=Jerusalem, Frisch, and Jewish law |url=http://blogs.timesofisrael.com/jerusalem-frisch-and-jewish-law/ |work=The Jewish Standard |publisher=Times of Israel |date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\nHe then became an associate editor with the [[North American Newspaper Alliance]] (NANA);<ref name=\"Sid_Goldberg\">{{cite news |last1=Associated |first1=Press |title=News Service to End 58 Years of Operation |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/nashua-telegraph-feb-21-1980-p-20/ |work=The Nashua Telegraph |agency=The Nutting Company |publisher=Ogden Newspapers |date=21 February 1980 |archivedate=2 September 2015 |location=New Hampshire |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/> at the age of 25, Engelmayer became the editor.<ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/><ref name=\"Mosquitia\">{{cite book |last1=Rangel |first1=Marc |title=Memories of Mosquitia |date=2009 |publisher=Xlibris Corporation |isbn=9781477163191 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LJ5W6Ey6nq0C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"SDE_Liddy\">{{cite news |last1=Wire Story |title=Ford Linked to Job Assist for Liddy |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/phoenix-arizona-republic-oct-16-1973-p-21/ |work=The Arizona Republic |agency=Associated Press |publisher=USA Today Network |date=16 October 1973 |language=en}}</ref>  [[United Features Syndicate]] (UFS) acquired and absorbed NANA, and from 1972 to 1979, Engelmayer edited under the banner of UFS.<ref name=\"UFS_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon |last2=Ashman |first2=Charles |title=Nixon Leaves pepsi firm, Meets Mitchell, Martha Meets the Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/101240600/ |work=The Cincinnati Enquirer |publisher=USA Today Network |date=25 July 1973 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe became the first editor of [[Jack Anderson (columnist)|Jack Anderson]]'s \"[[Washington Merry-Go-Round]]\" column and was a part of Anderson's winning of the [[Pulitzer Prize]].<ref name=\"BW_SDE\">{{cite news |title=Future Events |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=27kiAQAAMAAJ&dq= |work=[[Business Week]] |issue=2287-2294 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |date=1973}}</ref><ref name=\"palmer_Mask\">{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Joanne |title=The man in the mask |url=http://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/the-man-in-the-mask/ |work=Jewish Standard |publisher=Times of Israel |date=26 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis own investigative work writing about the American natural gas shortage in the Seventies won him the [[Thomas L. Stokes]] Award for National Reporting, Washington Journalism Center.<ref name=\"Stokes Award_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Robert |last2=Engelmayer |first2=Sheldon |title=Public Utilities Skirt Gas Issue |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/high-point-enterprise-may-03-1976-p-1/ |work=High Point Enterprise |agency=hpenews.com |date=3 May 1976 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Star News\">{{cite news |last1=Associated |first1=Press |title=S-N Columnists Win Stokes Writing Prize |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/star-news-mar-16-1976-p-15/ |work=Star News |agency=Associated Press |date=16 March 1976 |archiveurl= |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s and 1980s, Engelmayer was almost a regular on the [[Barry Farber]] radio show, with Farber calling him \"the big Shamm\",<ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=SSSJ Events, 1964-1991. Boxes 1-51 and Oversized Boxes 197 & 385 |url=http://libfindaids.yu.edu:8082/xtf/view?docId=ead/SSSJ/SSSJ.xml;query=;brand=default |website=Yeshiva University Archives |publisher=Yeshiva University |location=Mendel Gottesman Library |page=248}}</ref> referring to his Hebrew name, Shammai, which he began using professionally once he became a pulpit rabbi.<ref name=\"CBI_Palisades\">{{cite web |title=Meet Our Rabbi |url=http://cbiotp.org/Our-Rabbi.html |website=cbiotp.org |publisher=CONGREGATION BETH ISRAELOF THE PALISADES}}</ref><ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/>\n\nIn the early 1980s, Engelmayer replaced David Gross as the executive editor of the ''[[New York Jewish Week]]'',<ref name=\"JTA_SDEJW\">{{cite news |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon |title=Full-Term Miracle, May 14, 1948 |url=http://ufdc.ufl.edu/AA00010090/03145 |work=The Jewish Floridian |agency=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |issue=19 |volume=62|date=12 May 1989 |page=5}}</ref><ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/><ref name=\"JJG_SDE\">{{cite book |last1=Goldberg |first1=J.J. |title=Jewish power : inside the American Jewish establishment |date=1996 |publisher=[[Basic Books]] |location=Reading, Mass. |isbn=9780201622423 |page=xi |edition= 3rd printing |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Jewish_Power.html?id=BwV2AAAAMAAJ}}</ref><ref name=\"Gross_Dies\">{{cite news |title=News Brief {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency |url=https://www.jta.org/2005/09/28/archive/david-gross-a-former-writer-for-jta-and |work=www.jta.org |publisher=JTA |date=28 September 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"Bard-Gross\">{{cite book |last1=Bard |first1=Mitchell G. |title=From tragedy to triumph : the politics behind the rescue of Ethiopian Jewry |date=2002 |publisher=[[Praeger Publishing]] |location=Westport (Conn.) |isbn=9780275970000 |page=153 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sjO8JOSKDCMC&dq=David+Gross+Jewish+Week&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> a New York-based Jewish issues weekly newspaper.  He left in 1991 and took a post as director of communications for the [[Jewish Theological Seminary of America|Jewish Theological Seminary]] in New York City,<ref name=\"JTS_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Wire |title=Bat Mitzvah Pioneer Marks Another Religious Milsteon |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sedalia-democrat-mar-20-1992-p-3/ |work=Sedalia Democrat |agency=Associated Press |date=20 March 1992}}</ref><ref name=\"DNC_Shammai\">{{cite news |last1=Nussbaum Cohen |first1=Debra |title=Camp\u2019s Decision to Censor Magazine Illustrates Rift Among Conservatives {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency |url=https://www.jta.org/1994/09/30/archive/camps-decision-to-censor-magazine-illustrates-rift-among-conservatives |work=Daily News Bulletin |agency=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |publisher=www.jta.org |date=30 September 1994}}</ref> where he also renewed his rabbinical ordination, preparing him for his pulpit position.\n\nHe was also briefly the editor of the ''[[MetroWest Jewish News]]'' from 1996-1998.<ref name=\"Lorell_SDEMW\">{{cite news |last1=Lorell |first1=Mark |title=Congressional report warns:  War in Middle East is imminent {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency |url=https://www.jta.org/1997/06/05/life-religion/features/congressional-report-warns-war-in-middle-east-is-imminent |work=www.jta.org |agency=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |date=5 June 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, Engelmayer established an award-winning column (\"Keeping the Faith\") for the New Jersey-based weekly newspaper ''[[The Jewish Standard]]'', in which he discusses current issues through the prism of Jewish law. He was the editor of ''The Jewish Standard'' until he resigned in 2012. He continued his weekly column, but now had time to teach and run his synagogue, which has since merged with three other synagogues that were dwindling in numbers and looking for new leadership.<ref name=\"palmer_Mask\"/><ref name=\"Shabbus\">{{cite news |last1=Santora |first1=Alexander |title=Jews in North Bergen get a Shab-Bus to shul |url=https://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2014/11/jews_in_north_bergen_get_a_shab-bus_to_shul.html |work=[[Jersey Journal]] |agency=NJ.com |date=19 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"CommMarriage\">{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Joanne |title=A community marriage |url=https://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/a-community-marriage/ |work=[[The Jewish Standard]] |publisher=Times of Israel |date=5 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"SSB_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Solomon Bernstein |first1=Susan |title=Temple Beth El Has Closed, But It is Not Gone |url=https://zicharonot.com/2016/01/15/temple-beth-el-has-closed-but-it-is-not-gone/ |work=zicharonot |date=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, he and his frequent writing partner, Robert Wagman, NANA's Washington, D.C., bureau chief, produced a documentary called ''The Making of [[Lion of the Desert]]'',<ref name=\"MakinLOTD\">{{cite web |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon |last2=Wagman |first2=Bob |title=The Making of Lion of the Desert |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2983612/ |date=1981}}</ref> a film about pre-WWII fascist Italy, starring [[Anthony Quinn]], [[Oliver Reed]], and [[Rod Steiger]].\n\n===Rabbinate===\nOrdained as an [[Orthodox Jewish]] rabbi in 1967,<ref name=\"TBEBC\">{{cite web |title=Rabbi Shammai Englemayer |url=http://www.templebethelofnorthbergen.org/about/rabbi-shammai-englemeyer/ |website=Temple Beth El of North Bergen |publisher=Temple Beth El Bergen County}}</ref> he chose the field of journalism.  In 1992, while working at the Jewish Theological Society he also enrolled in rabbinate courses and recertified his ordination through the Conservative Jewish movement. His first pulpit was the Lake [[Hopatcong, New Jersey|Hopatcong]] Jewish Center in New Jersey.<ref name=\"Common_Ground\">{{cite book |last1=Ozarowski |first1=Joseph S. |last2=Engelmayer |first2=Shammai |last3=Sofian |first3=David M. |editor1-last=Lipman |editor1-first=Steve |title=Common ground : the weekly Torah portion through the eyes of a Conservative, Orthodox, and Reform rabbi |date=1997 |publisher=[[Jason Aronson]] |location=Northvale, N.J. |isbn=9780765759924 |page=391 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=03T6u7nh9MQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>  He would find a congregation closer to his home, Temple Israel in [[Cliffside Park, New Jersey|Cliffside Park]], and merged with other neighboring congregations.<ref name=\"CommMarriage\"/>\n\n===Personal life===\nEngelmayer was married to Roslyn Engelmayer,<ref name=\"NYSC\">{{cite journal |title=Reports of cases decided in the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of the state of New York |date=1978 |page=756 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0a5OAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=8 August 2011 |publisher=the University of California |location=Digitized |language=en |quote=Alimony}}</ref> and then to the writer, [[Marilyn Henry]], who died in 2011.<ref name=\"Boroson\">{{cite news |last1=Boroson |first1=Rebbecca |title=Former \u2018Post\u2019 staffer Marilyn Henry dies, 58 |url=https://www.jpost.com/Features/In-Thespotlight/Former-Post-staffer-Marilyn-Henry-dies-58 |work=The Jerusalem Post |publisher=JPost.com |date=3 March 2011}}</ref> He has three children and lives in [[Teaneck, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Boroson\"/>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n* [[Simon Rockower Award|Rockower Award]] in 2011 for Commentary/2nd place, The Standard (for an article on President Obama's stance on Israel.<ref name=\"Obama\">{{cite news |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Shammai |title=Obama\u2019s distorted Israel image |url=https://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/obamas-distorted-israel-image-4/ |work=The Standard |publisher=Times of Israel |date=6 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"JTA2013Rock\">{{cite news |last1=JTA Staff |title=Excellence in Jewish journalism: The Rockower Awards {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency |url=https://www.jta.org/2013/06/28/news-opinion/the-telegraph/excellence-in-jewish-journalism-the-rockower-awards |work=www.jta.org |agency=Jewsish Telegraphic Agency |date=28 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AJYB2013\">{{cite book |last1=Sheskin |first1=edited by Arnold Dashefsky, Ira |title=American Jewish Year Book 2013 The Annual Record of the North American Jewish Communities |date=2014 |publisher=Springer International Publishing |location=Cham |isbn=9783319016580 |page=817 |edition= Aufl. 2014 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FQTABAAAQBAJ&dq=}}</ref> It is noteworthy is that back in 1978\u201379 Engelmayer had held President [[Jimmy Carter]] accountable for what he and his co-author Robert Wagman called \"broken promises\" over wage and price controls, defence spending, and nuclear proliferation.<ref name=\"Carter_SDE\">{{cite news |last1=Wagman |first1=Robert |last2=Engelmayer |first2=Sheldon |title=Promises, Promises, More Broken Promises, Part II |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/santa-ana-orange-county-register-evening-feb-27-1979-p-4/ |work=[[Santa Ana Orange County Register]] |publisher=Southern California News Group |date=27 February 1979 |page=B17}}</ref>\n* Rockower Award in 2010 - First Place for Editorial Writing,<ref name=\"AJPA2010\">{{cite web |last1=Category 4: Award for Excellence in Editorial Writing |title=The 31st Annual Simon Rockower Award Winners - American Jewish Press Association |url=https://www.ajpa.org/page/2012RockowerAwards |website=www.ajpa.org}}</ref> in 2005 for Commentary/2nd place, [[American Jewish Press Association]], Rockower Award for Commentary/2nd place, AJPA, 2004, Rockower Award for Editorial Writing/1st place, American Jewish Press Association, 1990\n* Rockower Award for Editorial Writing/2nd place, AJPA, 1989\n* Rockower Award for Editorial Writing/1st place, AJPA, 1988,<ref name=\"E&P1988\">{{cite book |title=Editor & Publisher |date=1990 |publisher=Editor & Publisher Company |page=2 |edition= Vol 123 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CU1IAQAAIAAJ&q=Rockower+Award+1988+Engelmayer&dq=Rockower+Award+1988+Engelmayer&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTqMOXjMzcAhUE74MKHYBoBksQ6AEIKTAA |language=en}}</ref>\n* Thomas L. Stokes Award for National Reporting, Washington Journalism Center, 1975<ref name=\"Hostage\">{{cite book |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon D. |last2=Wagman |first2=Robert J. |title=Hostage |date=1981 |publisher=Caroline House Publishers |location=Ottawa, Ill. |isbn=0898030846 |url=https://www.amazon.com/HOSTAGE-OP-Sheldon-D-Engelmayer/dp/0898030846/ref=sr_1_4?ie=UTF8&qid=1533152692&sr=8-4&}}</ref>\n* In 1975, he won the Washington Journalism Center's [[Thomas L. Stokes]] Award for National Reporting.<ref name=\"Star News\"/>\n* Media Humanitarian Award, National Association of Justice, 1974\n\n==Books==\n* ''Martha: The Mouth that Roared''<ref name=\"MM\">{{cite book |last1=Ashman |first1=Charles |last2=Engelmayer |first2=Sheldon |title=Martha: The Mouth That Roared |date=1973 |publisher=Berkley |isbn=978-0425024683}}</ref><ref name=\"Ashman_MM\">{{cite news |last1=Ashman |first1=Charles |title=Martha - The Mouth that Roared|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/journal-news-jul-24-1973-p-16|work=Journal News - Hamilton Ohio |agency=Cox Media Group |date=24 July 1973 |archiveurl= |archivedate= |location=Ohio |page=16 |language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Lord's Justice''<ref name=\"Lord'sJustice\">{{cite book |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon |last2=Wagman |first2=Robert |title=Lord's justice |date=1985 |publisher=Anchor Press/Doubleday |location=Garden City, N.Y. |isbn=978-0385230513 |edition=1st |url=https://archive.org/details/lordsjustice00enge }}</ref>\n* ''HUBERT HUMPHREY The man and His Dream''<ref name=\"HubertHumphrey\">{{cite news |last1=Library News |title=Through These Doors |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/huntingdon-daily-news-dec-04-1978-p-17/ |work=Huntingdon Daily News |agency=The Daily News |publisher=Sample News Group |date=4 December 1978 |language=en}}</ref> \n* ''Hostage''<ref name=\"Hostage\"/>\n* ''Tax revolt 1980: A how-to guide''<ref name=\"Tax Revolt\">{{cite book |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Sheldon D. |last2=Wagman |first2=Robert J. |title=Tax revolt 1980 : a how-to guide |date=1980 |publisher=Arlington House Publishers |location=Westport, CT |isbn=0870004697 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Tax-revolt-1980-how-guide/dp/0870004697/ref=sr_1_5?ie=UTF8&qid=1533152692&sr=8-5&keywords=}}</ref>\n* ''Where there's smoke (A Last Resort Mystery Book 1)''<ref name=\"Smoke\">{{cite book |last1=Engelmayer |first1=Shammai |title=Where there's smoke |date=27 November 2012 |publisher=Amazon Digital Services LLC |url=https://www.amazon.com/Where-theres-smoke-Resort-Mystery-ebook/dp/B00AEGD1VA/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1533153286&sr=8-1}}</ref>\n* ''Common Ground''<ref name=\"Common_Ground\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/writers/shammai-engelmayer/ Jewish Standard]\n* [http://shammai.org Shammai.org]\n* [http://www.betshammai.com/ Bet Shammai Blog], named for the school of thought of Judaism founded by [[Bet Shammai|Shammai]], a Jewish scholar of the 1st century, whose arguments were the better ones, but were the least adhered to over his rival, [[Bet Hillel]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Engelmayer, Sheldon}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:American Conservative rabbis]]\n[[Category:American Orthodox rabbis]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Teaneck, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rabbis from New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shammai_Engelmayer"}
